```{r, include = FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(collapse = TRUE, comment = "#>", fig.path = "figure/",
                      fig.width = 6, fig.height = 5, dpi = 96, error = FALSE)
```

The Harmonized Landsat Sentinel-2 (HLS) project delivers a common surface
reflectance product from two sensors, giving a land observation every 2-3 days
at 30 m. The two collections are spectrally harmonized but **name their bands
differently and carry different band sets** (Landsat has thermal bands and no
red edge; Sentinel-2 has red edge and a broad NIR). This vignette harmonizes
both onto one band schema, builds a cloud-masked median composite, and reduces
the band axis to its first three principal components. It uses the Microsoft
Planetary Computer, which is pre-signed and fast.

## Discover and harmonize

Query both collections over an area of interest, filter cloudy scenes, and drop
duplicate acquisitions.

```{r discover, message = FALSE}
library(garry)

aoi <- c(144.24, -7.66, 144.36, -7.54)   # lon/lat bbox
mpc <- "https://planetarycomputer.microsoft.com/api/stac/v1/"

query <- function(collection) {
  its <- stac_query(bbox = aoi, stac_source = mpc, collection = collection,
                    start_date = "2023-01-01", end_date = "2023-12-31")
  rstac::items_sign(its, rstac::sign_planetary_computer())
}
```

Each collection's assets are mapped onto one shared schema with
`stac_rename_assets()`: aerosol `A`, visible `B`/`G`/`R`, red edge
`RE1`-`RE3`, NIR `N` (broad) and `N2` (narrow), water vapour `WV`, cirrus `C`,
SWIR `S1`/`S2`, thermal `T1`/`T2`. Unmapped assets (view angles, previews) drop
out, so the map doubles as the band selector. `stac_merge()` concatenates the
two harmonized tables.

```{r harmonize}
l30 <- stac_sources(query("hls2-l30")) |>
  stac_filter_cloud(80) |> stac_drop_duplicates() |>
  stac_rename_assets(c(
    B01 = "A", B02 = "B", B03 = "G", B04 = "R", B05 = "N2", B06 = "S1",
    B07 = "S2", B09 = "C", B10 = "T1", B11 = "T2", Fmask = "Fmask"))

s30 <- stac_sources(query("hls2-s30")) |>
  stac_filter_cloud(80) |> stac_drop_duplicates() |>
  stac_rename_assets(c(
    B01 = "A", B02 = "B", B03 = "G", B04 = "R", B05 = "RE1", B06 = "RE2",
    B07 = "RE3", B08 = "N", B8A = "N2", B09 = "WV", B10 = "C", B11 = "S1",
    B12 = "S2", Fmask = "Fmask"))

src <- stac_merge(l30, s30)
cat("bands:", paste(sort(unique(src$asset)), collapse = " "), "\n")
```

No empty-band padding or reordering is needed (unlike a VRT-based approach):
`lazy_dataset()` gives each band only the slices that carry it, and `mask()`
pairs a band's slices with the matching Fmask by name. A Landsat-only thermal
band and a Sentinel-only red-edge band each reduce over exactly their own
observations.

## Cloud-masked median composite

```{r composite}
# Thermal (T1/T2) is Landsat-only and sparse, so requiring it drops most pixels
# from the PCA; keep the reflectance/red-edge bands, which both sensors provide.
bands  <- c("A", "B", "G", "R", "RE1", "RE2", "RE3", "N",
            "N2", "WV", "C", "S1", "S2")
target <- grid_from_bbox(aoi, res = 30)     # equal-area 30 m grid

garry_daemons()

comp <- lazy_dataset(
  src, grid = target, assets = bands, mask_asset = "Fmask",
  nodata = c(stats::setNames(rep(-9999, length(bands)), bands), Fmask = 255)
) |>
  mask(from = "Fmask", where = qa_bits(0:3), open = 2, dilate = 3) |>
  reduce_over("median", over = "t")
```

```{r truecolour}
preview(comp, bands = c("R", "G", "B"))      # true-colour look (band names)
```

## PCA over the band axis

A per-pixel PCA collapses the spectral vector to a few components. Fit it in
plain R on the materialized composite -- fitting a model in R is perfectly
reasonable; not everything belongs in the lazy graph.

```{r pca-fit}
cube <- stack_bands(comp)                    # LazyRaster (band, y, x)
arr  <- collect(cube)                        # (y, x, band)
px   <- matrix(arr, ncol = dim(arr)[[3]])
px   <- px[stats::complete.cases(px), , drop = FALSE]
pca  <- prcomp(px, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)
round(summary(pca)$importance[, 1:3], 3)     # variance explained, PC1-3
```

The projection onto each principal component is a **linear combination of the
bands** -- exactly `reduce_over(over = "band")`. `band_project()` builds the
reducer (centre, then weight by the loading); stacking the first three gives a
3-band image. Because it is lazy, the same projection runs chunked and
distributed at full resolution without ever holding the whole cube in memory.

```{r pca-project}
sc  <- pca$scale                             # prcomp(scale. = TRUE): weights /= sd
pcs <- lazy_stack(
  lapply(1:3, function(i)
    reduce_over(cube, band_project(pca$rotation[, i] / sc, center = pca$center),
                over = "band")),
  along = "band")

preview(pcs)                                 # PC1-3 as R/G/B
```

```{r cleanup, include = FALSE}
garry_daemons(0, 0)
```

The same `band_project()` reducer is the basis for any linear-model `predict`
(regression, logistic, unmixing): fit in R, pass the coefficients as `weights`.
Non-linear models (random forests, boosting) don't trace to the compute
backend -- for those, `collect()` the composite and predict in R.
